listen the first question you know i intend to be specific like you suggested
but the first question i just wanted to to have you say a little bit about the

00:49.940 --> 01:00.060
origin or genesis of underwood miller you know how you got together and started
it? Yeah, I'd be glad to, because it's kind of an unusual story, as far as

01:00.060 --> 01:09.040
business partnerships are concerned. In 1975, I

01:09.040 --> 01:20.440
decided I wanted to publish a book. Specifically I wanted to publish The Dying
Earth in a hardcover form. I was a used book dealer, and Chuck Miller was a used

01:20.440 --> 01:31.520
book dealer dealing in rare and out-of-print books and some new material and we
knew of each other and I think we had bought and sold books from each other from

01:31.520 --> 01:44.920
time to time and Chuck heard about I may have mentioned in a letter about The
Dying Earth and Chuck offered his expertise because he knew a good deal about

01:44.920 --> 01:57.500
certain parts of publishing industry about distribution and that end of it. And
my experience, my limited experience, had to do with just graphically putting a

01:57.500 --> 02:09.640
book together. And so he suggested that we do the book together. And so we did.
And the interesting thing is that we never met each other until the book had

02:09.640 --> 02:22.560
already been published. And that was a year later in 1976. six and up to that
time we were literally exchanging thousands of dollars to the mail and doing

02:22.560 --> 02:33.700
business without without ever having met each other we were in a sense complete
strangers but we had this one connection and that is we both felt strongly about

02:33.700 --> 02:44.140
this one work of vance of the dying earth and about vance's work in general and
about specifically about fantasy and science fiction and horror and literature.

02:44.940 --> 02:56.420
And we had that association. And the fact is that that literary genre, fantasy
and science fiction, most of the people in it seem to be honest, or at least

02:56.420 --> 03:06.860
most of the people dealing in it professionally as book dealers and book buyers.
And so it worked out well. A year later we met in Kansas City at a convention

03:07.920 --> 03:17.560
selling the Dying Earth and selling some other books. and since then, we've gone
on and have published, I think it's up to 43 books now, I haven't counted.

03:18.260 --> 03:25.400
Mostly Vance, but some other authors also, Zelazny and Williamson

03:25.400 --> 03:42.380
and Robert E. Howard and Stephen R. Donaldson and a few others. so that's that's
the general background I met Vance in the course of publishing the dying earth I

03:43.360 --> 03:54.940
wrote him a letter and he wrote back and he's uh in the same general vicinity
and hours drive from my house and he wrote back and said come over and I did and

03:54.940 --> 04:06.280
we struck up quite a friendship and A few years later, Jack attended a
convention out east and met Chuck, and the three of us spent some time together.

04:07.100 --> 04:18.940
More as friends than anything else. Our association has been through the book,
through publishing Jack's books, but our relationship has really not been one of

04:18.940 --> 04:31.340
business at all. We have business maybe twice a year when we pay royalties to
them or we send them a contract, but it's a very casually done and doesn't

04:31.340 --> 04:33.040
really figure too much in the relationship.

04:38.000 --> 04:46.640
I'd say that's the background. Yeah, that's fine. That's excellent. As long as
you brought up Jack Vance already, why did you think Dying Earth was special?

04:46.760 --> 04:58.540
What was the impetus there for wanting to publish that one? Well, at that time,
and in fact it's even more true today, A lot of science fiction and fantasy, and

04:58.540 --> 05:11.640
sometimes the best of it, does not get published in hardcover editions. And what
Chuck and I do is we publish high-quality hardcover books for collectors in

05:11.640 --> 05:23.740
limited editions and for libraries on acid-free paper and with library binding
like that. And we publish small editions. And our editions are too small,

05:23.740 --> 05:40.480
really, for a mainstream New York publisher like Harper & Row or Doubleday to
bother with. They have to publish 5,000 books in hardcover just to break even

05:40.480 --> 05:49.440
with their advertising and their overhead. We can publish an edition of a
thousand or fifteen hundred and do all right because we don't have a large

05:49.440 --> 06:01.000
overhead and our advertising consists of essentially specialty bookstores in our
mailing list. We also sell the libraries extensively, but that doesn't require

06:01.000 --> 06:14.420
much advertising. So we're filling a slot there. And The Dying Earth was the
first book we did. And it was just a book that is essentially a classic. It was

06:14.420 --> 06:26.640
published in 1950 as a paperback. And it had never been in hardcover. And it's
just one of the outstanding books in the fantasy field. And 200 years from now,

06:26.660 --> 06:35.820
people will be reading it. And it had never been in a durable hardcover edition.
And so we put it in one and sold it to collectors and sold it to libraries and

06:35.820 --> 06:46.920
did very well with it. Do you eventually intend to do all of Vance's work or
just selected items? I would say most of it, a good deal of it, simply because

06:46.920 --> 06:49.400
we have our association with Vance.

06:52.120 --> 07:09.240
And a number of our clients are Vance fans and collect Vance. And a lot of what
Vance has written is good. Vance, of course, is among a lot of other fantasy and

07:09.240 --> 07:15.080
science fiction writers, has written his share of forgettable

07:15.080 --> 07:24.620
fiction. But a lot of what he's written is really memorable and worth
preserving. And Vance, like other science fiction and fantasy writers like Fritz

07:24.620 --> 07:36.840
Leiber and Philip K. Dick and Ursula Le Guin and any number of people you could
name, had the bulk of their work published in paperback. And these books never

07:36.840 --> 07:51.240
saw a hardcover edition simply because of the economics of the time. so yeah we
are publishing other authors now but we will continue to publish Vance's work

07:51.240 --> 08:04.760
because we both enjoy reading it and we think it's significant literature in
other words part of your concern there is to make sure that work you think is

08:04.760 --> 08:11.460
significant is made permanent so it's available to readers that's it, just to
preserve the work that was the original That and just the pleasure of

08:11.460 --> 08:22.920
bookmaking, just the pleasure. Chuck and I both take a great pleasure in making
a good book, a book that has its signature sewn, which is something that doesn't

08:22.920 --> 08:32.640
occur in general trade hardcover publishing anymore, a book that's printed on
acid-free paper so that in 20 or 30 years the paper won't turn brittle and

08:32.640 --> 08:44.900
brown, and just a well-made, well-bound book, attractively made and artistically
put together. And publishing a book like that, creating a book like that is

08:44.900 --> 09:00.980
really a pleasure. And of course, your listeners may care to know that, or they
may not understand that a publisher is not a printer. A publisher,

09:01.340 --> 09:12.760
traditionally, has always just been the person who creates the book and
organizes the book as a package, as a book, not as a novel. The writer writes

09:12.760 --> 09:24.620
the fiction, and the publisher sees that it's manufactured, but as of today, no
major publisher owns any printing equipment. I think Doubleday was the last

09:24.620 --> 09:33.720
house that actually owned some printing equipment, and they no longer do, and
we're the same way. Our books are manufactured in Michigan, and I live in

09:33.720 --> 09:47.380
California, and Chuck Miller lives in Pennsylvania, and we do everything at a
distance. We design the books, and we decide as to what size they're going to be

09:47.380 --> 09:56.520
and who's going to illustrate them if they're illustrated. We make the editorial
choice of deciding what books to publish and when and how many copies to print,

09:56.520 --> 10:06.040
and those kind of decisions. And then the book is sent off to a printer, and the
book is printed and bound, and then shipped back to us. And so that is

10:06.040 --> 10:17.400
essentially what we do. And we do it, Chuck and I do it together, talking on the
phone once or twice a week, and through the mail. If I remember, some of your

10:17.400 --> 10:25.200
earlier books, in the back it said that they had been printed, I thought, or the
typography or the printing was somewhere in San Francisco. Now, what's that got

10:25.200 --> 10:35.880
to do with Michigan? I'm not sure. the the first book that we did was was
manufactured in san francisco and the second book that we did was manufactured

10:35.880 --> 10:52.340
in um in illinois in indiana the first book we did was manufactured in san
francisco the second book was by donnelly in indiana and then the third book and

10:52.340 --> 11:03.240
and all the books since then Save One, which was printed up in Vermont, but most
of them have been in mid-Michigan. There's a reason for that. We're doing what's

11:03.240 --> 11:17.160
called short print runs, which is 1,000, 1,500 copies. And there are printers in
the Michigan area who are set up to do that length of print run. They can do

11:17.160 --> 11:26.460
that length of print run very economically. For example, whoever is printing
Vikings books, and actually most of them are printed in Brattleboro, Vermont,

11:27.660 --> 11:38.500
that particular printer is set up to do from 5,000 to 100,000 books, and they
like to do 20,000 or 30,000 at minimum, and that's where they're economical.

11:39.020 --> 11:50.920
They can't do 1,000 books. To do 1,000 books there would cost a great deal of
money. By the same token, because of the size of their press and the size of

11:50.920 --> 12:06.740
their shop, the printer that we use in the mid-Michigan area in Ann Arbor is set
up to do from 500 to 1,500 books, and that's their niche. And just because of

12:06.740 --> 12:15.840
the size of the press and the size of the shop and a number of other factors, is
depending upon how many books you're printing and what kind of book and what

12:15.840 --> 12:24.940
quality of book you want printed, you have to shop around and find the best
place to do it. And it took us a year or two to really find our stride, to find

12:24.940 --> 12:35.520
the right printer who could print a very high-quality book in a limited edition
and yet at a reasonable price. And when we found one, we stuck with them. Good,

12:35.600 --> 12:47.440
okay. I understand better now. Say for a book by Vance, What's a normal run of a
cloth book like that? And how do you determine how many you're going to do? Why

12:47.440 --> 12:59.580
not more, if you can sell them? You're thinking of our print run now. Yeah. The
books we do. Right. Okay, we normally do... Well, Green Magic, for example, is 1

12:59.580 --> 13:13.460
,500 copies. Some of them are as few as 500 copies. We're primarily publishing
for collectors. When we have a book that's essentially a new collection, like

13:13.460 --> 13:27.020
Green Magic was, or it's a first hardcover edition, a book that's never been out
as such before, which Galactic Effectuator was, we might do a few more, but

13:27.020 --> 13:42.860
generally we stay around 1,000 copies or 1,500 copies. And there's a couple
reasons for that. One is we're selling to collectors, and the collectors are

13:42.860 --> 13:55.880
buying these books with the knowledge that they're going to go out of print and
become valuable later on. Another reason is that Chuck and I don't own a

13:55.880 --> 14:08.380
warehouse, and we are not in business to have a large inventory. We couldn't, we
would make more money if we printed more books. Because as you print more books,

14:08.520 --> 14:11.780
the cost per book of manufacturing goes down dramatically.

14:15.220 --> 14:24.980
But we just simply can't afford to have a lot of books in inventory sitting
around. We can't afford, our books go out of print in about nine months. And

14:24.980 --> 14:35.300
this is just the opposite of a major manufacturer like Dutton or Brown or
someone like that. They want their book to stay in print as long as possible.

14:35.640 --> 14:47.980
And we want our books to go out of print as soon as possible. And the reason for
that being that, well, a couple of reasons. One, we are manufacturing and

14:47.980 --> 15:00.840
selling with a book collector in mind. And a lot of these people are investors.
And they are essentially investing in our books. another reason being that it's

15:00.840 --> 15:11.540
a simple economic reason that Chuck and I are just due to economics are turning
our money over as fast as we can because we don't have an unlimited source we

15:11.540 --> 15:25.900
don't deal with banks the way a major publisher is essentially dealing with a
printer and dealing with banks and a big factor in their business is is the

15:25.900 --> 15:36.920
interest rate because they're dealing in borrowed money and we are not. We're
using our own money and just continuing to reinvest it in what we're doing and

15:36.920 --> 15:46.980
that's how we operate and that's why we're printing very few books. Okay, fine.
