18:23.920 --> 18:42.700
Well, Chuck and I share similar tastes. Our criteria is first that the author be
good and be writing something that's worthwhile. and again we're speaking of

18:42.700 --> 18:54.660
most of the books we're talking about are within fantasy science fiction and
horror genres second they have to have a certain popularity there are some

18:54.660 --> 19:06.180
authors who are who are good who are not collectible or are not popular and we
simply can't afford to publish people like that there are a few people like that

19:06.180 --> 19:20.720
that we would like to publish but cannot we may from time to time do one book by
them we would like to do a book by Avram Davidson who's really quite a good

19:20.720 --> 19:31.520
writer and there are some other writers that we will be doing that may or may
not be collectible and may not be saleable and writers who are trying to do new

19:31.520 --> 19:43.360
things Carl Wagner's trying to do some new things within the horror field and we
may be publishing him but essentially we're taking authors who are already well

19:43.360 --> 19:55.420
-known and popular and whose work has some significance, and because they're not
getting published in hardcover, or in the case maybe of Ursula Le Guin, because

19:55.420 --> 20:06.520
the way that they're making hardcovers these days is so poor of quality, that
these authors want a hardcover edition of their work that's going to be durable

20:06.520 --> 20:19.480
and well-made. And the fact is that the hardcover publishers simply economically
can't do it because they can't sell enough to make it worth their while. So we

20:19.480 --> 20:30.940
step into that void that simple economics, the fact that Japan bought a lot of
lumber in this country and drove the price of paper up, and just other factors

20:30.940 --> 20:43.140
which have driven up the price of books and cut down the number of new books
being published. Odd situations such as the fact that the tax law changed last

20:43.140 --> 20:55.520
year and now publishers are getting stuck with tax for their inventory. And this
is a whole new situation, and it's causing publishers not to have inventory and

20:55.520 --> 21:04.800
to be more careful about what books they publish. So there again, you have fewer
new titles published each year. This is a trend that's going to continue, and

21:04.800 --> 21:15.680
more and more paperback originals. And as long as that trend continues, there
will be a need for people like us who are publishing a small number of hardcover

21:15.680 --> 21:25.320
books for libraries and for people who want to have a library of their own in
their house. Very good. Okay, excellent. Listen, why did you get into the

21:25.320 --> 21:37.180
bibliography aspect of it? What was the intention there? Again, it was in the
